<P>
GOLIATH FROGS: THE JURY IS OUT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Directors of the Calaveras County Fair have postponed a decision on allowing 
African Goliath frogs to compete in the annual frog-jumping contest after the 
state attorney general's office told them it would be illegal to meet in secret 
on the matter. Instead of a secret executive session Friday on a possible rules 
change that would ban the huge frogs from the contest, the directors will use 
the gathering to solicit public comment, said Diane Baumann of the 39th 
District Agricultural Assn., which hosts the May 17-20 contest. A Seattle man's 
plan to win the $1,500 in prize money by entering Goliath frogs, which are up 
to three feet long and reportedly can jump 30 feet or more in a bound, has 
attracted worldwide publicity to the contest, made famous in a Mark Twain short 
story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
